   <abstract >Meta-analysis is a widely used tool for synthesizing results from multiple studies. As such, it plays an essential role in evidence-based medicine and clinical decision-making. However, a few concerns may seriously affect the validity of the conclusion from systematic reviews and meta-analyses, as well as the robustness of decision-making. One critical problem in meta-analyses and systematic reviews is that outlying studies are frequently included, which can bias the results of synthesizing evidence. Outliers may be caused by several factors, such as study selection criteria, low study quality, etc. Although outlier detection is well-studied in the statistical community, limited attention has been paid to meta-analysis. Another major concern is publication bias or small-study effects, which is led by the phenomenon that studies with statistically significant results are more likely to be published than those with non-significant results. Several SE-based and sample-size-based regression tests were proposed to assess small-study effects and publication bias. However, studies' direction and sample size calculation are rarely accounted for. This dissertation aims to address these problems and strengthen the validity of systematic reviews and meta-analyses. For outlying studies, we propose a sensitivity analysis using an iterative framework with bagging to detect outlying studies efficiently and make valid inferences. Simulation studies showed that the iterative method can produce less bias, higher coverage probability, and better detection accuracy. Insights from a statistical perspective can be provided for further analyses. For small-study effects and publication bias, we propose a directional test to control type I error rates and improve the statistical power. The directional test can better control the type I error rates and produce higher power than the other competitors. Furthermore, we use a simulation study that takes account of sample size calculation to illustrate the unaddressed issue in sample-size-based regression tests for publication bias. The inflated type I error rates indicate that the underlying assumptions and the good properties of the sample-size-based tests may be challenged.</abstract>
